New results of Swedish age tests for asylum seekers published
The latest results of the medical age tests of asylum seekers in Sweden have been published.The results of the new assessment methodology reveal that more than 80% of those tested were determined to be over 18 years of age.
The Swedish National Forensic Agency started testing earlier this year.
The tests allow a more accurate assessment of the age of the asylum seeker, a new test introduced after criticism of the Swedish Migration Agency for failing to determine the actual age of applicants who claimed to be minors.
The Migration Agency has carried out 6 880 tests to date and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of 2 481 tests, which were carried out between mid-March and the end of July 2017.
Of the 2002 asylum seekers tested, 80% were determined to be over 18 years of age, and in 25 cases the Forensic Office determined that the test subject was possibly 18 years of age or older.
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the asylum seeker was possibly under 18 years of age.
The tests were only carried out in cases where there were reasons to doubt the age claimed by the applicant.
The results are consistent with those of previous months, says Johan Göransson, of the Forensic Medicine Office.
The figures are fairly consistent, with no major differences from previous months, he told The Local.
Although a large proportion of applicants were identified as being over 18 years of age, this does not necessarily mean that applicants lied about their age.
In May, the Agency published the results of 581 tests and reported that 442 cases had 'indications that the subject was 18 years of age or older'.
When Svenska Dagbladet examined the same results, it was found that in 243 cases the applicant had openly said that he would turn 18 this year.
The medical method of age assessment used in the tests, which involves X-rays of the wisdom teeth and magnetic images of the kneecaps, is also criticized by dentists and radiologists.
One of the skeptics is endocrinologist Claude Marcus of the Caroline Institute, whose work involves assessing the biological maturity of humans to determine whether a person has reached puberty earlier or later than usual.
I have had reason to think about this and I do not think the method used is the right one.
Determining biological age in this way is highly uncertain.
If we cannot determine age with certainty, we should not pretend we can", he told Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson of the Forensic Office defended the accuracy of the tests: In general, the risk of determining the child as an adult is low.
The risk is highest when the test subject is about to turn 18 years old, when the risk is about 10%.
