The Bank of England keeps interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce that it will keep rates unchanged once economic growth has been flat and the slowdown in inflation has ended speculation about interest rate hikes.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will continue to slow, and it has postponed interest rate hikes because of increasing pressure on household income levels.
The decision-makers of the central bank's monetary policy committee voted 62 to keep interest rates at 0.25%, an increase that has been even less popular this month because of the stagnation in economic growth.
In its quarterly inflation survey, the Bank lowered its growth forecast for 2017 to 1.7% and for 2018 to 1.6% and warned of further pressure on household income levels as inflation is expected to continue to accelerate to close to 3% in the autumn.
However, the Bank believes that interest rate increases will be needed in the coming years to contain Brexit-induced inflation and that borrowing costs may have to rise more than expected in financial markets.
The Committee also decided to withdraw part of the massive economic package that was launched a year ago in the wake of the Brexit referendum.
The Bank will close the Term Funding Scheme in February 2018, although it is now expected to provide an additional GBP 15 million, or a total of GBP 115 million, of low-cost funding to banks through the scheme.
The Bank's minutes of the interest rate decision state: The Monetary Policy Committee forecasts that the slowdown in GDP will continue in the coming years, as the fall in real household incomes dampens consumption.
On interest rates, the Bank reiterated that to contain inflation, some monetary policy tightening was needed slightly more broadly than market expectations.
The market is currently forecasting a first increase in the third quarter of 2018 and a second in 2020.
The Bank stressed, however, that any increases would be gradual and limited.
In May, the Bank forecast growth of 1.9% for this year and 1.7% for next year.
It now kept its growth forecast for 2018 at 1.8%.
The pound weakened against the dollar and the euro as a result of the news.
The pound fell by 0.5% to $1.31 against the dollar and by 0.4% to €1.11 against the euro.
The decision to keep rates unchanged was taken after weaker than expected growth levels dampened expectations of higher interest rate increases.
The Bank expects growth to remain stable at 0.3% in the third quarter but to pick up slightly at the end of the year.
Its latest inflation survey gave little hope for households suffering from soaring inflation and meager wage increases, and the bank said the situation would get worse before it gets better.
The Bank added that monetary policy could not prevent the decline in income in the coming years, but that it expected wage developments to recover significantly at the end of the three-year forecast period.
The economy will also be strengthened by strong growth in demand for British products as a result of the weak pound, which will offset some of the impact of the fall in private consumption.
The decision came a year after interest rates were cut to 0.25% following a shock EU referendum result that sent the pound plummeting.
The Bank considers that the full effects of the decision are likely to start to be felt in terms of prices and the economy only after four years.
Prior to the recent decision by the central bank, demands for rate increases had become more and more vocal as inflation increased pressure on households.
Inflation eased to 2.6% last month from 2.9% in June, but the Bank said it was expected to tighten again in the coming months.
According to the Bank, the excess over its 2% target was overall due to the weak pound.
