The NHS reported that PrEP is prescribed to about 10,000 people during the first three years of the trial.The drug, taken before intercourse, has been shown to reduce the risk of infection by about 86 per cent in high-risk individuals.
The NHS agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld a Supreme Court ruling last year that the NHS could pay for PrEP, even though it claims that local authorities should fund it.
The NHS England chief, Simon Stevens, called Thursday's decision "a significant new intervention" and the national AIDS organisation described it as "a decisive moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first to start accepting registrations for the trial, which will be extended to other clinics in October.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medicine that is taken before sex to reduce the risk of infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV infections in those at risk.
Taking a medicine before sex means that you have enough medicines in your body to prevent HIV infection during sex.
You can take it every day or two hours before sex.
The target group is gay, bisexual and transgender men and people with an HIV-positive partner who are not receiving effective treatment.
Clinics select eligible applicants from men, women and transgender people, as well as from those whose HIV-positive partner is not known to be receiving antiretroviral treatment for their disease.
People living in England and enrolled in GP care can also apply for a trial at their local sexual health clinic.
The programme costs £10 million and the NHS in England signed a procurement agreement for the drugs this week following an international tender.
The aim of the trial is to assess the potential of PrEP by collecting extensive clinical evidence on its targeting, administration and delivery.
This significant new intervention should complement and enhance the already diverse and increasingly effective means of HIV prevention, says Stevens.
Another major achievement in the more than 30-year fight to tackle one of humanity's greatest health challenges.
This is a critical moment in the fight against HIV, says Deborah Gold, director of the National AIDS Foundation.
If PrEP is properly targeted at those who need it and at risk, it could have a major impact on the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, a trial funded by the NHS will give people at risk a medicine they can decide on on their own, without the need to consult a partner, with a powerful impact that will improve the lives of so many people.
This was welcome news.
It is now crucial to ensure that the trial is launched quickly across the country and that no one at risk is left out, says Ian Green, Director of the Terrence Higgins Foundation.
The PrEP drug used in the trial has been procured and we will soon be able to protect tens of thousands of people at risk from HIV infection.
The launch of the PrEP trial is a welcome development, which was delayed for months by government delays, says Shadow Health Minister Sharon Hodgson.
We have evidence that the drug can have a revolutionary impact on the work we are doing to prevent HIV and stop the spread of this menacing disease.
