Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate may help relieve irritable bowel syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like digestive nightmares.
However, recent research suggests otherwise - a diet rich in meat protein and dairy may alleviate irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritable bowel syndrome is a chronic condition that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, causing abdominal cramps, swelling, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Although people with irritable bowel syndrome are generally advised to avoid meat and dairy products, researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan, which is found in protein, helps the body to develop immune cells that strengthen the intestinal lining.
According to Marco Colonna, the study's leader, immune cells guard the salt and prevent harmful microbes from entering the body.
The cells that cause inflammation are balanced by cells that strengthen the immune system, which protects the body without damaging delicate tissue.
If the balance drops too close to the inflammation, the result can be irritable bowel syndrome.
The tests showed that resistance-boosting immune cells are present in mice that have a particular bacterium in their gut.
The bacteria in question need tryptophan to start producing immune cells, which is one of the building blocks of proteins.
We found a link between Lactobacillus reuteri and the development of resistance-promoting cells. Lactobacillus reuteri is part of the normal gut microbiome, says Professor Colonna.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more they had these immune cells.
If the same is true in humans, a combination of Lactobacillus reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan may improve intestinal tolerance and reduce susceptibility to inflammation.
In studying resistance-boosting immune cells, researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that while one group of mice had such cells, the mice of the same species kept separate from the other group did not.
He suspected that the difference was due to the microbiome of the mice's gut, the normal community of bacteria, fungi, and viruses in the digestive tract.
When the gut DNA of the mice was examined, six types of bacteria were found in the mice that had immune cells but not in the other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri was administered to mice raised in a sterile environment, which had no gut microbiome and had not developed immune cells, they began to develop immune cells.
To find out how the bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in liquid and transferred small amounts of the liquid  without bacteria  from mice to immature immune cells isolated from the mice.
The immune cells evolved into endurance-boosting cells.
When the active substance was purified from the liquid, it was found to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism, known as indoli-3 lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's diet, the number of resistance-boosting cells increased by about 50 percent.
Cervantes-Barragan says that humans have the same immune-boosting cells as mice, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri in our digestive tract.
It is not yet known whether tryptophan byproducts cause cells from Lactobacillus reuteri to develop in humans in the same way as in mice, but genetic defects associated with tryptophan have been observed in patients with irritable bowel syndrome.
We probably want to promote the development of these cells because they regulate inflammation on the inner surfaces of the intestines, says Cervantes-Barragan.
High tryptophan levels in combination with Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria may contribute to their prevalence.
