The White House exhibit cost the taxpayers thousands of dollars .
The White House's decision last month to fly a Navy helicopter to the White House's south lawn for an event showcasing American manufactured goods came at a cost to taxpayers of $24,000, according to a report obtained by TIME magazine from military documents.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, which is called Marine One when the president is on board, was the centerpiece of an event at the White House on July 17, 2017, to showcase American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and a group of White House officials were able to view products from all 50 states.
In addition to a Connecticut-made helicopter, the exhibit included a sailboat from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a truck from Mississippi.
The White House Military Office had requested the helicopter to be on site by mission order only about 36 hours before it landed on the south lawn for an "exceptional" event, according to Navy HMX-1 helicopter fleet records.
I just wanted to make sure you were aware of this because it is an exceptional event that will get a lot of publicity, the commander of HMX-1 wrote in an email the day before the event to his supervisor, who is the assistant commander of the Naval Aviation.
The message said that the helicopter would arrive at the south lawn at 7 a.m. on July 17 and that the event would begin at 3 p.m. and that the helicopter would not leave until the lawn was cleared between 6 and 9 p.m.
The message also stated that if the helicopter was delayed from the White House, additional crew would be needed due to the time constraints.
The original crew was on the helicopter during the incident and unit security personnel were with the helicopter while it was on the ground.
The documents obtained by TIME magazine do not indicate whether another crew was needed.
The Hatch Act of the United States of America prohibits federal employees from using government property for political purposes.
According to the files, HMX-1 was investigating whether the incident violated the law.
One of our questions was whether this was a violation of the Hatch Act, and we were told that it was not, the commander wrote.
"Sounds like you're up for it", replied the deputy commander.
Made in America was an official White House event, so it was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
At the event, the president spoke in favor of health care reform, which was then under consideration by the Senate, and looser government regulation.
The use of Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is not a new phenomenon.
Presidents must wear them when they travel.
But using them for just photographs is unusual.
Trump's actions drew attention in February when Air Force One rolled into the background of a presidential campaign event in Melbourne, Florida.
"The White House is very pleased with the Made in America event, which showcased products made by American workers from all 50 states using American materials", said White House press secretary Lindsay Walters.
The crews of HMX-1 regularly conduct training flights in the Washington area and practice on the south lawn to bring the president into the White House to within an inch of his actual range.
While Trump was in Germany for the G-20 summit in early July, the HMX-1 made 58 training landings on the White House.
According to one official, flights to the Made in America event were part of the crew's monthly training quota.
The unit also flew 11 hours of helicopters that day on non-presidential support missions.
The White House says the transaction did not cause any additional costs to the taxpayers.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company was not involved in the helicopter show on the south lawn of the White House.
HMX-1 has no records of presidential missions and an accurate estimate of the cost of the event is difficult.
According to the 2017 Department of Defense hourly compensation, the compensation level for a VH-3D helicopter is $24,380 per flight hour.
According to HMX-1 flight records, the total flight time from Quantico, Virginia to the White House and back was one hour.
The White House says the cost of running a helicopter is significantly lower.
Calculating the cost to taxpayers by level of compensation is misleading, says Walters.
The estimated level of compensation includes staff, maintenance and many other so-called 'embedded costs' which are taken into account in the annual appropriations.
The Commission notes that the Commission has not provided any evidence that the aid was granted in breach of Article 107 (1) TFEU.
At the time of the event, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of a helicopter in the event.
